      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Spear-phishing, a clever tactic employed by those sneaky goblins, often disguising themselves as legitimate emails. To help your staff spot these phishing attempts, I'd recommend focusing on the following red flags: \n\n1. Urgency: Be wary of emails that create a sense of urgency, such as \"Your account will be suspended if you don't click on this link within the next 24 hours.\" This is a classic tactic used by goblins to get you to act impulsively.\n2. Personalization: Phishing emails often contain personalized details, such as the recipient's name or company name. However, this can also be a red flag, as goblins might have obtained this information through social engineering or by hacking into your staff's accounts.\n3. Grammar and spelling mistakes: Goblins are notorious for their lack of attention to detail, so be on the lookout for grammatical errors, typos, or awkward phrasing in the email.\n4. Unusual sender information: Be cautious of emails with unfamiliar or spoofed sender addresses. Goblins often use fake email addresses to trick their victims.\n5. Requests for sensitive information: Phishing emails often ask for sensitive information, such as passwords, credit card numbers, or personal",
      "source": "target",
