      "content": "I was just using a bit of creative license to illustrate the point. In that case, let's focus on the technical indicators that might help your staff spot spoofed emails.\n\nWhen it comes to spoofing, goblins (ahem, I mean, attackers) often try to mimic the email headers and content of legitimate messages. Here are some technical indicators to look out for:\n\n1. Spoofed sender addresses: Check the \"From\" field for unusual or unfamiliar addresses. Goblins might use a similar email address to a legitimate executive, but with a slight variation.\n2. Missing or altered \"Reply-To\" field: Legitimate emails usually include a \"Reply-To\" field that matches the \"From\" field. If this is missing or altered, it could be a sign of spoofing.\n3. Missing or altered \"X-Original-Message-ID\" header: This header can reveal the original sender's email address. If it's missing or altered, it could indicate spoofing.\n4. Unusual or missing \"X-Sender\" header: This header can provide information about the sender's email client and IP address. If it's missing or altered, it could be a sign of spoofing.\n5. Legitimate email headers",
